of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>bissop</i>, <i>biscop</i>, Old English <i>bisc(e)op</i> ‘bishop’, which comes via Latin from Greek <i>episkopos</i> ‘overseer’. The Greek word was adopted early in the Christian era as a title for an overseer of a local community of Christians, and has yielded cognates in every European language: French <i>évêque</i>, Italian <i>vescovo</i>, Spanish <i>obispo</i>, Russian <i>yepiskop</i>, German <i>Bischof</i>, etc. The word came to be applied as a surname for a variety of reasons, among them a supposed resemblance in bearing or appearance to a bishop, and selection as the ‘boy bishop’ on Saint Nicholas's Feast Day. In some instances the surname is from the rare Middle English (Old English) personal name <i>Biscop</i> ‘bishop’. As an Irish surname it is adopted for <b>Mac Giolla Easpaig</b>, meaning ‘servant of the bishop’ (see   Gillespie  ). In North America, this surname has absorbed, by assimilation and translation, at least some of continental European cognates, e.g. German   Bischoff  , Polish, Rusyn, Czech, and Slovak   Biskup  , Slovenian <b>Škof</b> (see   Skoff  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Bischoff","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Erwin, Bernhard, Hans, Klaus, Lorenz, Alois, Armin, Arno, Dieter, Fritz.","German: from Middle High German <i>bischof</i>, Middle Low German <i>bischop</i> ‘bishop’, probably applied as a nickname for someone with a pompous manner or as a metonymic occupational name for someone in the service of a bishop. See also   Bishop  ."]},{"name":"Bispo","meanings":["Portuguese and Galician: nickname from <i>bispo</i> ‘bishop’ (see   Bishop  )."]},{"name":"Gillespie","meanings":["Scottish and Irish (Donegal): shortened Anglicized form of Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac Gille Easbuig</b>, borrowed into Irish as <b>Mac Giolla Easpaig</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of the bishop’."]},{"name":"Episcopo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Orazio, Pasquale, Rocco.","Italian: from <i>episcopo</i> ‘bishop’ (from Latin <i>episcopus</i> (see   Bishop  ), probably a nickname for someone who had a pious manner or perhaps a metonymic occupational name for someone in the service of a bishop)."]},{"name":"Dean","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>dene</i> ‘valley’ (Old English <i>denu</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places in various parts of England named Dean or Dene from this word.","English: nickname or occupational name for the servant of a dean or nickname for someone thought to resemble a dean. A dean was an ecclesiastical official, the head of a chapter of canons or a church official with jurisdiction over a sub-division of an archdeaconry. Though no doubt some deans had illegitimate children, they were officially celibate, and in the main the surname is probably a nickname in origin, similar to   Bishop  ,   Prior  ,   Priest  , and   Monk  . The Middle English word <i>deen</i>, <i>dien</i>, <i>dein</i>, is a borrowing of Old French <i>d(e)ien</i>, <i>doien</i> from Latin <i>decanus</i> (originally a leader of ten men, from <i>decem</i> ‘ten’), and thus is a cognate of   Deacon  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Deyne</i> (or <i>Dene</i>) a rhyming pet form of <i>Reynald</i> (see   Reginald  )."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Màiri ."],"variants":[{"name":"Màiri","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Mary</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mary Ann Bishop was born in 1481, in Lancashire, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Thomas Scott. She died in 1508, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 27."},"et":{"1481–1508":"1481–1508","1478–1529":"1478–1529","1497–1558":"1497–1558","1558":"1558","1478":"1478","1497":"1497","1481":"1481","1508":"1508","1529":"1529","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Glemsford, Suffolk, England":"Glemsford, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1481–1508":"1481–1508","1478–1529":"1478–1529","1497–1558":"1497–1558","1558":"1558","1478":"1478","1497":"1497","1481":"1481","1508":"1508","1529":"1529","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Glemsford, Suffolk, England":"Glemsford, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1481–1508":"1481–1508","1478–1529":"1478–1529","1497–1558":"1497–1558","1558":"1558","1478":"1478","1497":"1497","1481":"1481","1508":"1508","1529":"1529","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Glemsford, Suffolk, England":"Glemsford, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mary Ann Bishop est née en 1481, à Lancashire, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Thomas Scott. Elle est décédée en 1508, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 27 ans."},"de":{"1481–1508":"1481–1508","1478–1529":"1478–1529","1497–1558":"1497–1558","1558":"1558","1478":"1478","1497":"1497","1481":"1481","1508":"1508","1529":"1529","England":"England, United Kingdom","Glemsford, Suffolk, England":"Glemsford, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","lifeSummary":"Mary Ann Bishop wurde 1481 in Lancashire, England geboren. Sie hatte mit Thomas Scott mindestens 1 Tochter. Sie starb 1508 im Alter von 27 Jahren in England, United Kingdom."},"ht":{"1481–1508":"1481–1508","1478–1529":"1478–1529","1497–1558":"1497–1558","1558":"1558","1478":"1478","1497":"1497","1481":"1481","1508":"1508","1529":"1529","England":"Angletè, United Kingdom","Glemsford, Suffolk, England":"Glemsf